top.value: In the Americas, we developed new policies to address gender inequality in coffee production and trade and to support coffee smallholders to cope with climate change. We did so through dialogue platforms in 4 countries: Honduras, Nicaragua, Colombia and Peru, engaging private as well as public and Civil society actors. A national gender policy for the coffee sector was approved by the National Coffee Board of Honduras (CONAFCAFE) and endorsed by the President of Honduras. Similarly, a roadmap to deliver a national gender strategy for the country was developed in Colombia. Through Colombia's ‘Leadership for Life’ initiative we strengthened the leadership and advocacy skills of 200 female coffee farmers and 50 cooperatives and associations’ representatives. In 2020, this  ‘Leadership for Life’ initiative was scaled up to Nicaragua and Honduras. In Nicaragua, in collaboration with local communities and the private sector, we have developed and submitted a proposal to improve working conditions and encourage Climate Smart Agricultural Practices and measures to mitigate climate change. In Peru, together with the National Chamber of Coffee and Cocoa and the Ministry of Agriculture, we worked on the development of the National Coffee Action Plan 2030, a policy document (already adopted by the national government) that aims to guide the sector towards climate smart coffee production.

Bottom UP! Initiative (promoting a sustainable cotton & garment value chain from Ethiopian cotton to European consumers), match funded by the EU. This project promotes the adoption of responsible social & environmental practices by 14 cotton and garment factories and 2,000 cotton farmers along the value chain. The programme is partially implemented in Tigray, the region that was under a state of emergency in 2020. Despite the Covid-19 pandemic, the floodings  and the state of Emergency in Tigray, we were able to train 118 workers in ginneries on occupational health and safety (OHS) and cleaner production. 2.8 tonnes of improved cotton seeds were supplied to 554 cotton farmers (400 ha) and 832 cotton farmers (of which 125 were women) have been supported on integrated pest management and have access to improved seeds and crop protection inputs and their markets. We worked closely with Ethiopian Textile Industry, Development Institute (ETIDI), Ethiopian Textile and Garment Manufacturers Association (ETGAMA), and Ethiopian Cotton Producers Exporters and Ginners Association (ECPGEA), to train 728 workers to adopt Good Practices on safe working conditions. The global pandemic, the political instability (i.e. the Tigray conflict) but also the flooding in the Afar region, which affected the cotton farms, delayed the implementation and momentum of planned activities.  
tanneries have participated in cleaner leather production workshops. We have partnered with LIDI, Ethiopian Leather Industries Association (ELIA), UNIDO and GIZ to influence policy making in the leather sector in general. We partnered with LIDI to scale-up the adaptation of cleaner leather production, especially in chrome-free/less chrome leather for shoe upper upholstery. We organised a marketing visit for European buyers to 10 tanneries and leather product manufacturers. 10 tanneries and manufacturers were supported to participate in the 11th All African Leather Fair in Ethiopia.

As part of its programmes, Solidaridad builds compelling business cases to generate investment opportunities, mobilizing a blend of grants, equity and credits to obtain the financing needed to increase speed and scale and achieve long-term economic, environmental and social impacts.

This task force is a network-wide group of experts in the field of impact investment, and is responsible for support with regards to the development of bankable business models and the engagement of impact investors.  

In 2020, we invested strongly in the network wide capacity of the regional specialists on impact investment and access to finance. This resulted in the development of new proposals and initiatives to increase farmers’ access to finance. Examples are the development of credit scoring and micro-finance in West Africa, a loan-management platform for crop maintenance in Colombia and climate-funding proposals in India and Indonesia.
We systematized and analysed several impact investment projects and opportunities and drew important lessons for our future strategic direction: among the main valuable lessons is the need to shift away from the large ticket sizes (> 500,000 euros) towards smaller investment needs for SMEs, the so-called “missing middle”. Increased attention for the development of financial instruments for smallholders became evident.
To target the “missing middle”, we launched the PlusPlus platform in partnership with Lendahand, Cordaid and Truvalu, in 2020. In total, the platform disbursed 9 loans to 6 counterparts with a total amount of 160,000 euros. Funding has been secured to build the coming years a pipeline with suitable candidates for funding in the Central American, East African and South African regions. In 2020, the GOWN Platform that targets specifically women-led SMEs, was designed and pre-tested among 5 SMEs, in 2021 the platform will be validated among 50 SMEs.

As part of the Digital Innovation strategy we aim to develop a Network-wide IT platform and approach to support Solidaridad and its partners in analyzing producer performance in the relevant areas of entrepreneurial farming and good practices. These are benchmarked against various standards, including legal standards, market-based quality standards and sustainability (certification) standards. By applying Big Data comparison technology to this analysis, we can bring large numbers of farmers to the next level of sustainable production. As of mid 2017, senior IT capacity came in board throughout the Network and we started a much larger streamlining process of already existing IT solutions in the Network, towards a broader strategic platform offering a series of tools through a suite of apps.

As part of the Digital Solidaridad Sustainability Solutions (3S) strategy, this taskforce aims to develop an ICT platform and approach to support Solidaridad and its partners in analyzing producer performance in the relevant areas of entrepreneurial farming and good practices. These are benchmarked against various standards, including legal standards, market-based quality standards and sustainability (certification) standards. By applying Big Data comparison technology to this analysis, we can bring large numbers of farmers to the next level of sustainable production. We are currently using the data gathering and information delivering platform in collaboration with major companies and leading producer associations.digital solutions, such as Farmer Solutions and Business Solutions, but also remote sensing, a cattle grading app, and soil testing services, are used in most of Solidaridad’s projects, in- and outside the Practice for Change programme, helping about 320,000 farmers to manage their businesses and make informed decisions,

Addressing climate contentious issues in our work will enable us to drive climate policy in regions to create enabling environments for climate adaptation and mitigation impact globally. In 2019, we f developed the climate risk/vulnerability analysis and the Climate Smart Index (CSI), both tools to measure climate -risk responsiveness and adaptation measurement, as well as GHG calculators to measure GHG mitigation impact. We developed commodity-specific definitions and climate-risk responsive measures for coffee, cotton, palm oil, and  tea. 

The CSI was tested with 52,012 farmers in 4 different projects (sugarcane Brazil, sugarcane India, Coffee East Africa and Palm Oil Nicaragua). It is an important tool to assess the impact and effectiveness of climate smart (adaptation) practices at farm level.
